[3199.440774, "o", "\u001b[6;45Hd\u001b[9;22Hd and load\u001b[10;46Hd\u001b[11;13Hd\u001b[13;21Hdefined registry keys on Wind\u001b[14;22H\u001b[30m\u001b[103mdi\ni\u001b[m\u000frectory (for SAPI modules), or \u001b[30m\u001b[103mdi\u001b[16;20H\u001b[m\u000fd\u001b[17;11H\u001b[30m\u001b[103mi\u001b[18;6H\u001b[m\u000fdows \u001b[30m\u001b[103mdi\u001b[m\u000frectory (usually C:\\wind\u001b[19;15Hd\u001b[22;61Hd\u001b[23;49Hd (as you probably guessed\u001b[24;14Hders (e.g. [Foo]) are also silently ignored\u001b[27;40H\u001b[30m\u001b[103mi\u001b[28;42Hi\u001b[29;29Hi\u001b[30;18H\u001b[m\u000fd\u001b[31;36Hdden by user-defined\u001b[32;36Hd [HOST=] sections only work und\u001b[36;26Hd\u001b[37;4H\u001b[30m\u001b[103mi\u001b[38;54Hi\u001b[39;31H\u001b[m\u000fd\u001b[40;24Hdation.  If PHP can't find an expected\u001b[41;4H\u001b[30m\u001b[103mi\u001b[m\u000frective because it is not set or is mistyped, a default value will be used\u001b[44;57Hd\u001b[45;36Hd\u001b[46;31H\u001b[30m\u001b[103mi\u001b[48;41H\u001b[m\u000fd to bitwise operators and\u001b[55;29Hd\u001b[56;20Hd\u001b[58;26Hdenoted\u001b[59;36Hd\u001b[65;41Hd\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f14,22\u001b[67;4H\u001b[?25h"]
[3199.735926, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[m\u000fs"]
[3199.743238, "o", "\u001b[1;65r\u001b[H\u001b[32M\u001b[1;67r\u001b[5;3Hdi\u001b[6;53Hdi\u001b[9;3Hdi\u001b[14;30Hdi\r\u001b[20B; dynamically loaded extension (either a PHP extension or a Zend extension),\u001b[K\r\n; you may only use these constants *after* the line that loads the extension.\u001b[K\r\n\u001b[K\n;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;\u001b[K\r\n; About this file ;\u001b[K\r\n;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;\u001b[K\r\n; PHP comes packaged with two INI files. One that is recommended to be used\u001b[K\r\n; in production environments and one that is recommended to be used in\u001b[K\r\n; development environments.\u001b[K\r\n\u001b[K\n; php.ini-production contains settings which hold security, performance and\u001b[K\r\n; best practices at its core. But please be aware, these settings may break\u001b[K\r\n; compatibility with older or less security-conscious applications. We\u001b[K\r\n; recommending using the production ini in production and testing environments.\u001b[K\r\n\u001b[K\n; php.ini-development is very similar to its production variant, except it is\u001b[K\r\n; much more verbose when it comes to errors. We recommend using the\u001b[K\r\n; development version only in development environments, as errors shown to\u001b[K\r\n; application users can inadvertently leak otherwise secure information.\u001b[K\r\n\u001b[K\n; This is the php.ini-production INI file.\u001b[K\r\n\u001b[K\n;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;\u001b[K\r\n; Quick Reference ;\u001b[K\r\n;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;\u001b[K\r\n\u001b[K\n; The following are all the settings which are different in either the production\u001b[K\r\n; or development versions of the INIs with respect to PHP's default behavior.\u001b[K\r\n; Please see the actual settings later in the document for more details as to why\u001b[K\r\n; we recommend these changes in PHP's behavior.\u001b[K\r\n\u001b[K\n; \u001b[30m\u001b[103mdis\u001b[m\u000fplay_errors\u001b[K\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f97,3            1%\u001b[67;5H\u001b[?25h"]
