[3200.641545, "o", "\u001b[1;3H\u001b[m\u000f                    relying on the fact it is automatically initialized to an\u001b[2;3H                    empty string)\r\n; E_CORE_ERROR      - fatal errors that occur during PHP's initial startup\u001b[4;3HE_CORE_WARNING    - warnings (non-fatal errors) that occur during PHP's\u001b[5;3H                    initial startup\u001b[6;3HE_COMPILE_ERROR   - fatal compile-time errors\u001b[28X\u001b[7;3HE_COMPILE_WARNING - compile-time warnings (non-fatal errors)\u001b[5X\u001b[8;3HE_USER_ERROR      - user-generated error message\u001b[11X\u001b[9;3HE_USER_WARNING    - user-generated warning message\u001b[27X\r\n; E_USER_NOTICE     - user-generated notice message\u001b[11;3HE_DEPRECATED      - warn about code that will not work in future versions    \u001b[12;3H                    of PHP\u001b[52X\u001b[13;3HE_USER_DEPRECATED - user-generated deprecation warnings\u001b[15X\u001b[14;2H\u001b[51X\r\n; Common Values:\u001b[16;3H  E_ALL (Show all errors, warnings and notices including coding standards.)  \u001b[17;3H  E_ALL & ~E_NOTICE  (Show all errors, except for notices)\u001b[18;3H  E_COMPILE_ERROR|E_RECOVERABLE_ERROR|E_ERROR|E_CORE_ERROR  (Show only errors)\u001b[19;3HDefault Value: E_ALL\u001b[20;3HDevelopment Value: E_ALL\u001b[21;3HProduction Value: E_ALL & ~E_DEPRECATED\r\n; https://php.net/error-reporting\r\nerror_reporting =\u001b[92m E_ALL & ~E_DEPRECATED\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[30X\r\n\u001b[62X\n; This directive controls whether or not and where PHP will output errors,\u001b[26;3Hnotices and warnings too. Error output is very useful during development, but\u001b[27;3Hit could be very dangerous in production environments. Depending on the code\r\n; which is triggering the error, sensitive information could potentially leak\u001b[29;3Hout of your application such as database usernames and passwords or worse.\u001b[30;3HFor production environments, we recommend logging errors rather than\u001b[31;3Hsending them to STDOUT.\u001b[22X\r\n; Possible Values:\u001b[33;3H  Off = Do not \u001b[30m\u001b[103mdisplay \u001b[m\u000fany errors\u001b[34X\u001b[34;3H  stderr = Display errors to STDERR (affects only CGI/CLI binaries!)\u001b[6X\u001b[35;3H  On or stdout = Display errors to STDOUT\u001b[34X\r\n; Default Value: On\u001b[37;2H Development Value: On\u001b[38;3HProduction Value: Off\u001b[39;2H https://php.net/display-errors\r\ndisplay_errors =\u001b[92m Off\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[55X\r\n\u001b[70X\u001b[42;3HThe \u001b[30m\u001b[103mdisplay \u001b[m\u000fof errors which occur during PHP's startup sequence are handled\r\n; separately from display_errors. We strongly recommend you set this to 'off'\u001b[44;3Hfor production servers to avoid leaking configuration details.\u001b[11X\u001b[45;3HDefault Value: On\u001b[56X\u001b[46;3HDevelopment Value: On\u001b[47X\u001b[47;3HProduction Value: Off\u001b[56X\r\n; https://php.net/display-startup-errors\r\ndisplay_startup_errors =\u001b[92m Off\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[49X\r\n\u001b[67X\u001b[51;3HBesides displaying errors, PHP can also log errors to locations such as a\u001b[52;3Hserver-specific log, STDERR, or a location specified by the error_log \r\n; directive found below. While errors should not be displayed on productions\u001b[54;3Hservers they should still be monitored and logging is a great way to do that.\r\n; Default Value: Off\u001b[56;2H Development Value: On\u001b[57;3HProduction Value: On\u001b[58;2H https://php.net/log-errors\r\nlog_errors =\u001b[92m On\u001b[m\u000f\r\n\u001b[81X\u001b[61;3HDo not log repeated messages. Repeated errors must occur in same file on same\u001b[62;3Hline unless ignore_repeated_source is set true.\u001b[32X\u001b[63;3Hhttps://php.net/ignore-repeated-errors\u001b[7X\r\nignore_repeated_errors =\u001b[92m Off\u001b[m\u000f\r\n\u001b[16X\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f493,18         25\u001b[67;10H\u001b[?25h"]
[3201.167947, "o", "\u001b[?25l\b"]
[3201.173153, "o", "\u001b[1;3H\u001b[m\u000fCGI/FastCGI.\u001b[65X\u001b[2;3Hhttps://php.net/ini.sections\u001b[5X\r\n\u001b[74X\u001b[4;3HDirectives are specified using the following syntax:\u001b[19X\u001b[5;3Hdirective = value\u001b[18X\u001b[6;3HDirective names are *case sensitive* - foo=bar is different from FOO=bar.\u001b[7;3HDirectives are variables used to configure PHP or PHP extensions.\u001b[8;3HThere is no name validation.  If PHP can't find an expected\u001b[9;3Hdirective because it is not set or is mistyped, a default value will be used.\r\n\u001b[51X\u001b[11;3HThe value can be a string, a number, a PHP constant (e.g. E_ALL or M_PI), one\u001b[12;3Hof the INI constants (On, Off, True, False, Yes, No and None) or an expression\u001b[13;3H(e.g. E_ALL & ~E_NOTICE), a quoted string (\"bar\"), or a reference to a\u001b[14;2H previously set variable or directive (e.g. ${foo})\r\n\u001b[16X\u001b[16;3HExpressions in the INI file are limited to bitwise operators and parentheses:\u001b[17;3H|  bitwise OR\u001b[45X\u001b[18;3H^  bitwise XOR\u001b[64X\u001b[19;3H&  bitwise AND\u001b[6X\u001b[20;3H~  bitwise NOT\u001b[10X\u001b[21;3H!  boolean NOT\u001b[25X\r\n\u001b[33X\n; Boolean flags can be turned on using the values 1, On, True or Yes.\r\n; They can be turned off using the values 0, Off, False or No.\r\n\u001b[74X\u001b[26;3HAn empty string can be denoted by simply not writing anything after the equal\u001b[27;3Hsign, or by using the None keyword:\u001b[41X\r\n\u001b[77X\u001b[29;3Hfoo =         ; sets foo to an empty string\u001b[31X\u001b[30;3Hfoo = None    ; sets foo to an empty string\u001b[25X\u001b[31;3Hfoo = \"None\"  ; sets foo to the string 'None'\r\n\u001b[18X\u001b[33;3HIf you use constants in your value, and these constants belong to a\u001b[34;3Hdynamically loaded extension (either a PHP extension or a Zend extension),\u001b[35;3Hyou may only use these constants *after* the line that loads the extension.\r\n\u001b[19X\u001b[37;2H;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;    \u001b[38;3HAbout this file ;    \u001b[39;2H;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;\u001b[13X\r\n; PHP comes packaged with two INI files. One that is recommended to be used\r\n; in production environments and one that is recommended to be used in\u001b[42;3Hdevelopment environments.\u001b[50X\r\n\u001b[77X\u001b[44;3Hphp.ini-production contains settings which hold security, performance and\u001b[45;3Hbest practices at its core. But please be aware, these settings may break\u001b[46;3Hcompatibility with older or less security-conscious applications. We\u001b[47;3Hrecommending using the production ini in production and testing environments.\r\n\u001b[40X\n; php.ini-development is very similar to its production variant, except it is\r\n; much more verbose when it comes to errors. We recommend using the\u001b[51;3Hdevelopment version only in development environments, as errors shown to \u001b[52;3Happlication users can inadvertently leak otherwise secure information.\r\n\u001b[76X\u001b[54;3HThis is the php.ini-production INI file.\u001b[37X\r\n\u001b[20X\u001b[56;2H;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;    \u001b[57;3HQuick Reference ;   \u001b[58;2H;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;\u001b[9X\r\n\u001b[15X\n; The following are all the settings which are different in either the production\u001b[61;3Hor development versions of the INIs with respect to PHP's default behavior.  \u001b[62;3HPlease see the actual settings later in the document for more details as to why\u001b[63;3Hwe recommend these changes in PHP's behavior.\r\n\u001b[28X\n; \u001b[30m\u001b[103mdisplay\u001b[m\u000f_errors\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f97,3            1\u001b[67;9H\u001b[?25h"]
