[3204.340953, "o", "\u001b[1;3H\u001b[m\u000fE_USER_ERROR      - user-generated error message\u001b[2;3HE_USER_WARNING    - user-generated warning message\r\n; E_USER_NOTICE     - user-generated notice message\u001b[4;3HE_DEPRECATED      - warn about code that will not work in future versions\u001b[5;3H                    of PHP\u001b[6;3HE_USER_DEPRECATED - user-generated deprecation warnings\u001b[18X\u001b[7;2H\u001b[66X\u001b[8;3HCommon Values:\u001b[45X\u001b[9;3H  E_ALL (Show all errors, warnings and notices including coding standards.)  \r\n;   E_ALL & ~E_NOTICE  (Show all errors, except for notices)\u001b[11;3H  E_COMPILE_ERROR|E_RECOVERABLE_ERROR|E_ERROR|E_CORE_ERROR  (Show only errors)\u001b[12;3HDefault Value: E_ALL\u001b[58X\u001b[13;3HDevelopment Value: E_ALL\u001b[46X\u001b[14;3HProduction Value: E_ALL & ~E_DEPRECATED\u001b[11X\r\n; https://php.net/error-reporting\r\nerror_reporting =\u001b[92m E_ALL & ~E_DEPRECATED\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[40X\r\n\u001b[15X\u001b[18;3HThis directive controls whether or not and where PHP will output errors,\u001b[19;3Hnotices and warnings too. Error output is very useful during development, but\u001b[20;3Hit could be very dangerous in production environments. Depending on the code\u001b[21;3Hwhich is triggering the error, sensitive information could potentially leak\r\n; out of your application such as database usernames and passwords or worse.\u001b[23;3HFor production environments, we recommend logging errors rather than\u001b[24;3Hsending them to STDOUT.\u001b[37X\r\n; Possible Values:\u001b[26;3H  Off = Do not display any errors\u001b[44X\u001b[27;3H  stderr = Display errors to STDERR (affects only CGI/CLI binaries!)\r\n;   On or stdout = Display errors to STDOUT\u001b[29;3HDefault Value: On\u001b[26X\u001b[30;3HDevelopment Value: On\u001b[22X\u001b[31;3HProduction Value: Off\u001b[24X\r\n; https://php.net/display-errors\r\n\u001b[30m\u001b[103mdisplay_errors \u001b[m\u000f=\u001b[92m Off\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[49X\r\n\u001b[76X\u001b[35;3HThe display of errors which occur during PHP's startup sequence are handled\r\n; separately from display_errors. We strongly recommend you set this to 'off'\u001b[37;2H for production servers to avoid leaking configuration details.\u001b[38;3HDefault Value: On\u001b[39;2H Development Value: On\u001b[40;4Hroduction Value: Off\u001b[52X\u001b[41;3Hhttps://php.net/display-startup-errors\u001b[30X\r\ndisplay_startup_errors =\u001b[92m Off\u001b[44;3H\u001b[m\u000fBesides displaying errors, PHP can also log errors to locations such as a\u001b[45;3Hserver-specific log, STDERR, or a location specified by the error_log    \u001b[46;3Hdirective found below. While errors should not be displayed on productions\u001b[47;3Hservers they should still be monitored and logging is a great way to do that\r\n; Default Value: Off\u001b[49;3HDevelopment Value: On\u001b[54X\u001b[50;3HProduction Value: On\u001b[45X\u001b[51;3Hhttps://php.net/log-errors\u001b[46X\r\nlog_errors =\u001b[92m On\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[57X\u001b[54;3HDo not log repeated messages. Repeated errors must occur in same file on same\r\n; line unless ignore_repeated_source is set true.\u001b[56;2H https://php.net/ignore-repeated-errors\r\nignore_repeated_errors =\u001b[92m Off\u001b[m\u000f\r\n\u001b[19X\n; Ignore source of message when ignoring repeated messages. When this setting\u001b[60;3His On you will not log errors with repeated messages from different files or   \u001b[61;3Hsource lines.\u001b[62X\u001b[62;3Hhttps://php.net/ignore-repeated-source\u001b[41X\r\nignore_repeated_source =\u001b[92m Off\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[19X\u001b[65;3HThis setting is off by default.\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f500,1          25\u001b[67;17H\u001b[?25h"]
